d a provocative discussion of the role played by early ethnographers, such as Alfred Kroeber, in influencing which tribes would eventually receive federal recognition. Indians, Missionaries, and Merchants takes a fascinating, yet troubling, look at California’s past and its role in shaping the state today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFederal aid to IndiansxCalifornia. 0aFederal aid to IndianszCalifornia. 0aFederally recognized Indian tribesxCalifornia. 0aFederally recognized Indian tribeszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCommercexHistoryxCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCommercezCaliforniaxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with EuropeansxCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with EuropeanszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with other peopleszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissionsxHistoryxCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissionszCaliforniaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aalfred kroeber.  aamerican colonialism.  aamerican history.  aarchaeology.  acalifornia.  acalifornian history.  acolonial systems.  acolonialism.  aethnography.  aethnohistory.  afort ross.  ahistorical anthropology.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  aindigenous peoples.  alabor.  anative americans.  anative cultures.  anative identity.  anative peoples.  aoral history.  apolitical.  areligion.  aretrospective.  arussian mercantile colony.  arussian merchants.  asocial formations.  aspanish missionaries.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094035240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940352